'''Starship''' is a [[two-stage]], [[Reusable launch vehicle|fully reusable]], [[super heavy-lift launch vehicle]] under development by American aerospace company [[SpaceX]]. Currently built and launched from [[SpaceX Starbase|Starbase]] in Texas, it is intended as the successor to the company's [[Falcon 9]] and [[Falcon Heavy]] rockets,<ref>{{Cite web |last=Clark |first=Stephen |date=2025-07-16 |title=The ISS is nearing retirement, so why is NASA still gung-ho about Starliner? |url=https://arstechnica.com/space/2025/07/despite-chronic-letdowns-nasa-just-cant-quit-boeings-starliner/ |access-date=2025-07-16 |website=Ars Technica |language=en}}</ref> and is part of SpaceX's broader [[SpaceX reusable launch system development program|reusable launch system development program]]. If completed as designed, Starship would be the first fully reusable orbital rocket and have the highest payload capacity of any launch vehicle to date. As of {{SpaceX_Starship_Statistics/data|statsDate}}, Starship [[List of Starship launches|has launched]] {{SpaceX_Starship_Statistics|totalLaunches}} times, with {{SpaceX Starship Statistics|totalLaunchSuccess}} successful flights and {{SpaceX Starship Statistics|totalLaunchFailure}} failures.

The vehicle consists of two stages: the [[SpaceX Super Heavy|Super Heavy]] booster and the [[SpaceX Starship (spacecraft)|Starship spacecraft]], both powered by [[SpaceX Raptor|Raptor]] engines burning [[liquid methane]] (the main component of [[natural gas]]) and [[liquid oxygen]]. Both stages are intended to return to the launch site and [[VTVL|land vertically]] at the launch tower for potential reuse.<ref name="MH">{{Cite web |title=Musk hopes "Mechazilla" will catch and assemble the Starship and Super Heavy boosters for rapid reuse |url=https://phys.org/news/2021-08-musk-mechazilla-starship-super-heavy.amp |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240514151133/https://phys.org/news/2021-08-musk-mechazilla-starship-super-heavy.amp |archive-date=May 14, 2024 |access-date=May 14, 2024}}</ref> Once in space, the Starship upper stage is intended to function as a standalone spacecraft capable of carrying [[Human spaceflight|crew]] and [[Uncrewed spacecraft|cargo]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=January 8, 2025 |title=Starship's Seventh Flight Test |url=https://www.spacex.com/launches/mission/?missionId=starship-flight-7 |access-date=January 15, 2025 |website=SpaceX.com}}</ref> Missions beyond [[low Earth orbit]] would require multiple in-orbit [[Orbital propellant depot|refueling]] flights. At the end of its mission, Starship [[Atmospheric entry|reenters]] the atmosphere using [[Atmospheric reentry#Thermal protection systems|heat shield tiles]] similar to those of the [[Space Shuttle]].<ref name="Reichhardt-2021">{{Cite web |last=Reichhardt |first=Tony |date=December 14, 2021 |title=Marsliner |url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/air-space-magazine/marsliner-180979371/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220506104518/https://www.smithsonianmag.com/air-space-magazine/marsliner-180979371/ |archive-date=May 6, 2022 |access-date=June 10, 2022 |website=[[Air & Space/Smithsonian]] |language=en}}</ref> SpaceX states that its goal is to reduce launch costs by both reusing and [[Mass production|mass producing]] both stages.
	
SpaceX initially expressed ambitions to use Starship for [[SpaceX Mars colonization program|crewed missions to Mars]]<ref>{{Cite news |last=Harwood |first=William |date=May 28, 2025 |title=SpaceX loses contact with its Starship on 9th test flight after last 2 went down in flames |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/spacex-super-heavy-starship-launch-ninth-test-flight/ |access-date=2025-06-28 |work=CBS News |language=en-US}}</ref>; the plan was later revised to prioritize the nearer objective of returning [[Moon landing|humans to the Moon]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Williams |first=Matthew |date=2026-02-11 |title=SpaceX Makes a Huge Pivot, Wants to Build on the Moon Instead |url=https://www.universetoday.com/articles/spacex-makes-a-huge-pivot-wants-to-build-on-the-moon-instead |access-date=2026-05-23 |website=Universe Today |language=en}}</ref> SpaceX has also proposed a wide range of missions for Starship, such as deploying large satellites, [[space station]] modules,<ref name="space20230510">{{Cite web |last=Wall |first=Mike |date=May 10, 2023 |title=Vast Space to launch 1st private station on SpaceX rocket in 2025 |url=https://www.space.com/vast-space-private-station-spacex-launch-2025 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250208072215/https://www.space.com/vast-space-private-station-spacex-launch-2025 |archive-date=February 8, 2025 |access-date=February 13, 2025 |website=Space.com |language=en}}</ref> and [[space telescopes]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Clark |first=Stephen |date=October 18, 2023 |title=Astronomers say new telescopes should take advantage of "Starship paradigm" |url=https://arstechnica.com/space/2023/10/astronomers-say-new-telescopes-should-take-advantage-of-starship-paradigm/ |access-date=2025-06-28 |work=[[Ars Technica]] |language=en}}</ref> A crewed variant, the [[Starship HLS|Starship Human Landing System]], is being developed under a contract with [[NASA]] as part of the [[Artemis program]], with a docking test as part of [[Artemis III]], currently scheduled for 2027,<ref name="NASA-2023">{{Cite web |date=January 13, 2023 |title=Artemis III: NASA's First Human Mission to the Lunar South Pole |url=https://www.nasa.gov/missions/artemis/artemis-iii/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240107195237/https://www.nasa.gov/missions/artemis/artemis-iii/ |archive-date=January 7, 2024 |access-date=January 7, 2024 |publisher=NASA |language=en-US}}</ref> and a crewed [[Moon landing|lunar landing]] scheduled for 2028.<ref name="Ars-Berger-Artemis">{{Cite web |last=Berger|first=Eric|date=2026-02-27|title=NASA shakes up its Artemis program to speed up lunar return|url=https://arstechnica.com/staff/2026/02/nasa-shakes-up-its-artemis-program-to-speed-up-lunar-return/|access-date=2026-02-27|website=Ars Technica|language=en}}</ref> 

SpaceX began [[SpaceX Starship design history|developing concepts]] for a super heavy-lift reusable launch vehicle as early as 2005, with different names throughout the years. Starship's current design and name were introduced in 2018. Development has followed an [[Iterative and incremental development|iterative and incremental]] approach, involving a high number of test flights and prototype vehicles. The first full Starship rocket was [[Starship flight test 1|launched]] April 20, 2023, exploding four minutes after liftoff.<ref>{{Cite web |last=O'Callaghan |first=Jonathan |date=October 1, 2023 |title=Termination shock |url=https://aerospaceamerica.aiaa.org/features/termination-shock/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231022181656/https://aerospaceamerica.aiaa.org/features/termination-shock/ |archive-date=October 22, 2023 |access-date=November 19, 2023 |website=Aerospace America |language=en-US}}</ref> The program has failed to meet many of its optimistic schedule goals, with several setbacks in development, including the failure of the first four Block 2 upper stages in 2025.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Foust |first=Jeff |date=June 8, 2023 |title=NASA concerned Starship problems will delay Artemis 3 |url=http://spacenews.com/nasa-concerned-starship-problems-will-delay-artemis-3/ |access-date=2025-06-28 |work=Space News |language=en-US}}</ref>

== Description ==
When stacked and fully fueled, Starship has a mass of approximately {{cvt|5300|t|lb}},{{efn|Super Heavy [[Vehicle weight|dry mass]]: {{cvt|200|t|lb}}; Starship dry mass: {{cvt|100|t|lb}}; Super Heavy propellant mass: {{cvt|3400|t|lb}};<ref name="Sesnic-2021"/> Starship propellant mass: {{cvt|1500|t|lb}}.<ref name="Lawler-2019">{{Cite news |last=Lawler |first=Richard |date=September 29, 2019 |title=SpaceX's plan for in-orbit Starship refueling: a second Starship |url=https://www.engadget.com/2019-09-28-starship-refueling-spacex.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191208013940/https://www.engadget.com/2019/09/28/starship-refueling-spacex/ |archive-date=December 8, 2019 |access-date=December 31, 2021 |work=[[Engadget]]}}</ref> The total of these masses is about {{cvt|5300|t|lb}}.}} a diameter of {{cvt|9|m}}<ref>{{Cite web |last=Dvorsky |first=George |date=January 4, 2021 |title=SpaceX Will Try to 'Catch' Its Starship Boosters Instead of Landing Them |url=https://gizmodo.com/spacex-will-try-to-catch-its-starship-boosters-instea-1845983594 |access-date=2025-03-20 |website=Gizmodo |language=en-US}}</ref> and a height of {{cvt|121.3|m|}}.<ref name="Berger blocks" /> The rocket has been designed with the goal of being fully [[Reusable launch vehicle|reusable]] to reduce launch costs;<ref name="Inman-2021">{{Cite conference |last1=Inman |first1=Jennifer Ann |last2=Horvath |first2=Thomas J. |last3=Scott |first3=Carey Fulton |date=August 24, 2021 |title=SCIFLI Starship Reentry Observation (SSRO) ACO (SpaceX Starship) |url=https://ntrs.nasa.gov/citations/20210020835 |conference=Game Changing Development Annual Program Review 2021 |publisher=[[NASA]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211011134426/https://ntrs.nasa.gov/citations/20210020835 |archive-date=October 11, 2021 |access-date=October 12, 2021 |hdl=2060/20210020835 |url-status=live}}</ref> it consists of the [[SpaceX Super Heavy|Super Heavy]] [[Booster (rocketry)|booster]] and the [[SpaceX Starship (spacecraft)|Starship]] upper stage<ref name="Amos-2021">{{Cite news |last=Amos |first=Jonathan |date=August 6, 2021 |title=Biggest ever rocket is assembled briefly in Texas |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-58120874 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210811063944/https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-58120874 |archive-date=August 11, 2021 |access-date=May 30, 2022 |work=[[BBC News]]}}</ref> which are powered by [[SpaceX Raptor|Raptor (RSL) and Raptor Vacuum (RVac) engines]].<ref name="cnet-20211021">{{Cite news |last=Ryan |first=Jackson |date=October 21, 2021 |title=SpaceX Starship Raptor vacuum engine fired for the first time |url=https://www.cnet.com/science/spacex-starship-raptor-vacuum-engine-fired-for-the-first-time/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220609051830/https://www.cnet.com/science/spacex-starship-raptor-vacuum-engine-fired-for-the-first-time/ |archive-date=June 9, 2022 |access-date=June 9, 2022 |publisher=[[CNET]]}}</ref>

The bodies of both rocket stages are made from [[stainless steel]]<ref name="slashgear-20220923">{{Cite news |last=Shayotovich |first=Eli |date=September 23, 2022 |title=Why SpaceX's Starship Is Made Out Of Stainless Steel According To Elon Musk |url=https://www.slashgear.com/1022924/why-spacexs-starship-is-made-out-of-stainless-steel-according-to-elon-musk/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231121054701/https://www.slashgear.com/1022924/why-spacexs-starship-is-made-out-of-stainless-steel-according-to-elon-musk/ |archive-date=November 21, 2023 |access-date=November 21, 2023 |work=SlashGear}}</ref> and are manufactured by stacking and welding stainless steel cylinders.<ref name="Berger-2020b">{{Cite news |last=Berger |first=Eric |author-link=Eric Berger (journalist) |date=March 5, 2020 |title=Inside Elon Musk's plan to build one Starship a week—and settle Mars |url=https://arstechnica.com/science/2020/03/inside-elon-musks-plan-to-build-one-starship-a-week-and-settle-mars/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211206215109/https://arstechnica.com/science/2020/03/inside-elon-musks-plan-to-build-one-starship-a-week-and-settle-mars/ |archive-date=December 6, 2021 |access-date=December 16, 2021 |work=[[Ars Technica]]}}</ref> These cylinders have a height of {{cvt|6|ft|m|sigfig=3|order=flip}}, and a thickness of {{cvt|3.97|mm}}.<ref name="Berger-2020b" />

Domes inside the spacecraft separate the methane and oxygen tanks.<ref name="Berger-2020b" /> SpaceX has stated that Starship, in its "baseline reusable design", will have a payload capacity of {{cvt|100|–|150|MT|lb|sigfig=3}} to [[low Earth orbit]] and {{cvt|27|MT|lb}} to [[geostationary transfer orbit]].<ref name="SpaceX-users-guide">{{Cite web |date=March 2020 |title=Starship Users Guide |url=https://www.spacex.com/media/starship_users_guide_v1.pdf |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210806173133/https://www.spacex.com/media/starship_users_guide_v1.pdf |archive-date=August 6, 2021 |access-date=October 6, 2021 |website=[[SpaceX]]}}</ref>

